SEGA’s throwing shit at the wall and hoping it sticks.

By Hilary Goldstein | Posted: NOV, 19 2005 1:20 PM

I’ll never forget my first day of school. I was about five years old, and I’d just been dropped off. I was terrified until I actually walked in the room, and my teacher, Mr. Stevenson, said welcome. He was a folksy guy, really nice to me, wore this tacky flannel shirt, gave me snacks and introduced me to every student! He made me feel welcomed the entire time I was there, and to this day remains my favorite teacher.

When I fired up Sonic Adventure 2 four years ago, it was almost as if Mr. Stevenson himself had been cast to play Sonic’s main rival, Shadow. In contrast to Sonic’s cockyness and can-do attitude, Shadow was an overall problem solver who was understanding and patient. He even had flannel-padded shoes! Their banter remains some of my favorite in the series, and Shadow certainly made his mark as one of my favorite characters, due in part to him reminding me of Mr. Stevenson.

Now imagine Mr. Stevenson riding motorcycles with a gun killing aliens and trying to find that “damn fourth chaos emerald” in his iconic southern accent (real quote from the game by the way). That’s the Shadow! the Hedgehog solo game. Really off-putting, right? SEGA doesn’t seem to think so. Ever since they pulled out of console making, their heads are out of the game. It’s like when your friend downsizes and then loses their job, wife and has to sell their car.

Shadow’s Identity War

Ignoring the obviously bad justification disguised as a plot device of Shadow having amnesia, he acts wildly out of character in this entry. The game ultimately comes down to the idea of good vs evil, yada yada yada, but what I’m really interested in is the gameplay choices.

Apparently, SEGA’s inspiration for Sonic was Bill Clinton, and it sure fits that Shadow’s was Lamar Alexander. Much like Shadow, Alexander started off as a southern charmer making solutions and problem solving, but ended up completely forgetting who he was during his term in office, figuratively speaking, and ended up being a big disappointment to the populist wing of the GOP, kind of like how this game disappointed me.

If you look at it this way, you have to ask why would SEGA parallel Shadow’s character growth to the IRL progression of the Alexander Administration? The gold line they created in SA2 must have been a fluke, much like Lamar winning a term to begin with. Just like his re-election prospects, this game flopped HARD.

Could you imagine SEGA making a game where Sonic, Knuckles, or Tails are doing anything other than running around? If Shadow is as fast as Sonic, why does he need a motorcycle? If he’s as strong as Sonic, why does he need a gun? I digress, back to the story. Through a series of allegiance switches and lore dumps caused by the amnesia, Shadow can encounter multiple endings within the game, none of which fitting the character we’ve only known for 2 games.

For instance, Shadow can kill Dr. Eggman if he believes he’s a clone and wants to assert dominance over the other clones. Even if he thinks he’s a clone, Shadow should have the innate values to understand killing is wrong. So why does he do it? Why is Shadow suddenly some brutish figure who doesn’t care about if he kills or ruins lives? I guess Shadow thinks Eggman is as bad as the Department of Education!

In Sonic Adventure 2, Shadow tried to calm down as many people as possible after Gerald Robotnik’s broadcast aired and came to Sonic on saving the world, making the blue blur put his pride on a shelf. Shadow’s friendship with Amy was endearing, as she reminded him of Maria, and her love for Sonic, whether repulsive or not, was a massive reason as to why Shadow began questioning Eggman. If the current Shadow was in SA2, these moments being gone would’ve lost all nuance for Shadow, and he’d just fall into the background of Sonic’s already oversized cast, yet another parallel to Lamar.

www.thenewpress.com

By Kirk McLean

Published 9:08 PM, September 9th, 2003

Our society today has been broken. There is no other way to put it. We have been consumed by a gaping, irreconcilable anger, engulfing our media and our art as would a maelstrom, a ship stranded out at sea. The cultural zeitgeist of our once great nation, over these past few years, has shifted into an interminable echo chamber of the same commercialized faux-cynicism repeated over and over again to a nauseating degree. Every day I find myself confronted with yet another false Moses, claiming to have found the answer to gun violence or homelessness or greed or capitalism or politics, all for it to just be, once more, nothing but vitriolic bile and sensationalist hyperbole disguised as a ‘realist’s interpretation of the truth’. All of this hate, however, and none of it truly in the face of the unchecked voracity of a power-hungry, callous corporate destruction of our public services and Democratic system.

That is why, in this environment, when one finds true artistic expression, it is euphoric.

What I am referencing is the recent piece of political satire, ‘Letter Of A Lover’, which has been widely circulated online as of late. Within it is contained what may be one of the most earnestly blunt pieces of modern writing I have read this year. This is rageful in a sense. Yet it is rage with a purpose. One that does not claim to provide a solution. Only to critique that which stands in the way of one.

The key dynamic of the piece, the relationship between the two Bills, is brilliant. Their love affair is used as a means by which to both highlight the failures of their administrations and to scathingly critique the two men, especially in their capacity as leaders. It is a torrid, broken affair; yet, much like in the story of genesis, the two are brought back to the forbidden fruit of their irresistible, corrosive love.

However, one of the most intriguing parts of the work to me is the characterization.

The fact is, the character of Weld is portrayed in a manner simultaneously exaggerated and pointedly accurate. He is cowardly. He is wracked by a sense of despair. He is anxious. His stress and fear are projected outwards towards others, manifesting in a bumbling, emotional man, with a slightly pathetic disposition towards self-deprecation and insecurity. In truth, this image of Weld, as a man wracked not so much by wickedness, but rather weakness, may be more accurate than the portrait of a cold-hearted creature of political delinquency we see purported by the major pundits of what remains of legacy liberal media.

Whilst this is obviously written from the perspective of Weld early on in his tenure, it is clear that there is little that has changed in the man over these torrid past 6 years. Observe his response to the Columbine hostage crisis 5 years ago, and his reaction to the LA bombings only a month fresh in this nation’s scarred mind. In both cases, he floundered, equivocated and stalled in an increasingly deteriorating mental state, until pressured by advisors to launch a botched intervention costing the lives of hundreds of Americans. He did not federalize the California National Guard in an act of strength; rather, it was in a desperate attempt to escape the supreme feeling of inadequacy which aides describe Weld as having possessed ever since he entered the White House. His relationship with Bill brings no different ails.

Clinton’s character, in contrast, is presented as ambiguous in his moral constitution; he bears no defining mark of evil, and brings with him no great indicator of good. This was much the case throughout his Presidency, and, as he edges ever closer to the shrinking circles of power Weld now surrounds himself with, it has become clear that the spectre of this snake oil salesman will not be exorcised from the highest office in the land anytime soon.

The recent press conference between Clinton and Weld should be only yet another stark indicator of how apt this piece is. Weld has not broken with Clinton or his failures in the slightest. He has continued cravenly on the blazing course of deconstructing the American social construct and remaking the American global order into a new machine of silent imperialism. Their personal friendship which has seemingly blossomed since the 1996 election should not be a surprise to anybody; the two men are both, in their own right, sickly embodiments of decadence and Western hubris. They find comfort and vindication in the fact that their broken status quo has a supporter in the form of the only type of person who matters to the political class; a fellow officeholder, acquainted to the struggles and mental contortion that come with the position.

I doubt that America, much like Weld, will ever escape the shadow of Clinton. The Democratic Party has collapsed into infighting after their calamity in the 2000 contingent election, all whilst under the thumb of a party apparatus still morbidly enamoured with the former President. The Reform Party is proving unable to sustain itself as a cohesive entity, even in the face of the encroaching ‘Uniparty’ they once warned of becomes an immanent reality. The newly formed ‘American Liberty Party’ offers no solution, its voice only melting into the violence and spite of the political scene. There seems to be no further respite for our current system.

But I digress. This is a review of a niche piece of writing online, not another one of those manifestos from a false prophet I so decried in the opening stages of this article. I will not encourage you to do anything further than read the original work in all its scathing beauty. And to the artistically inclined amongst you; if you still have a desire to rise above the noise, take notes. This is how one does it.

} processChart() { if (this.isProcessing) return; const element = document.getElementById("overall_result"); if (!element) return; const content = element.innerHTML; if (content.includes('class="ce-tooltip"')) { return; } this.isProcessing = true; let newContent = content; let hasChanges = false; // Debug: log what we're working with console.log('Original content:', content); // Create array of replacements sorted by key length (longest first) const sortedReplacements = Array.from(this.replacements.entries()) .sort((a, b) => b[0].length - a[0].length); console.log('Sorted replacements:', sortedReplacements.map(([key]) => key)); for (const [searchText, replacement] of sortedReplacements) { // Use word boundaries to ensure we only match whole words const regex = new RegExp(`\\b${searchText}\\b`, 'g'); if (regex.test(newContent)) { console.log(`Replacing: "${searchText}"`); newContent = newContent.replace(regex, replacement); hasChanges = true; } } if (hasChanges) { element.innerHTML = newContent; console.log('Final content:', newContent); } setTimeout(() => { this.isProcessing = false; }, 100); } init() { const checkAndProcess = () => { this.processChart(); }; this.intervalId = setInterval(() => { requestAnimationFrame(checkAndProcess); }, 200); } destroy() { if (this.intervalId) { clearInterval(this.intervalId); } } } const chartEnhancer = new ChartEnhancer();
